Author: Chao Lu, cl1486

Dataset: cleaned_twitter_withLabel.csv

Label:

"nft": NFT-related tweets
"Capflow": Market-Quotes-related tweets
"ethereum": ETH-related tweets
"bitcoin": BTC-related tweets

Stop words¶

In [162]:
A_STEMMER=PorterStemmer()
def MY_STEMMER(str_input):
    words = re.sub(r"[^A-Za-z\-]", " ", str_input).lower().split()
    words = [A_STEMMER.stem(word) for word in words] 
    return words

Data Vectorizeration¶

In [163]:
## Tf-idf vectorizer
MyTfidf=TfidfVectorizer(input='content',
                        stop_words='english',
                        # max_features=200,
                        tokenizer=MY_STEMMER,
                        lowercase=True
                        )

Crap words¶

In [164]:
text = ori_data['text']

Tfidf_data=MyTfidf.fit_transform(text)
DF_tfidf=pd.DataFrame(Tfidf_data.toarray(),columns=MyTfidf.get_feature_names())

stop_words = ['t','lqcijjjfmb','mfjqshwoso','s','denjytsey']
DF_tfidf = DF_tfidf.drop(stop_words,axis = 1)
DF_tfidf['label'] = ori_data['topic']

Train test split¶

In [165]:
# tfidf
TrainDF, TestDF = train_test_split(DF_tfidf,test_size = 0.3,random_state=1)
In [166]:
train_data = TrainDF.iloc[:,:-1]
train_label = TrainDF['label']

test_data = TestDF.iloc[:,:-1]
test_label = TestDF['label']

Tree 1¶

Visualization¶

In [167]:
## Instantiate

MyDT=DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', ##"entropy" or "gini"
                            splitter='best',  ## or "random" or "best"
                            max_depth=5, 
                            min_samples_split=2, 
                            min_samples_leaf=1, 
                            min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, 
                            max_features=10, 
                            random_state=3, 
                            max_leaf_nodes=None, 
                            min_impurity_decrease=0.0, 
#                             min_impurity_split=None, 
                            class_weight=None)

##
MyDT.fit(train_data, train_label)

feature_names=train_data.columns
topics = ori_data['topic'].unique()

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30,20))

_ = tree.plot_tree(MyDT, 
                   feature_names = feature_names,  
                   class_names=topics,
                   filled=True)
plt.title("Decision Tree 1", fontsize = 36)

# fig.savefig("decistion_tree1.png")

Discussion and analysis¶

By setting several parameters manually, such as "criterion='entropy'" and "splitter='best'", the final decision tree performs a simple tree plot.

Although the confusion matrix shows a pretty good result, it is mostly depending on manually deleting the crap words, where it increased the risk of overfitting. Generally, the accuracy of classification using the simple decision tree is low.

Some keywords or important features are play, volume, net, and bitcoin, where they are all the keywords belonging to each topic. For example, the "play" represents the culture of "NFT", the "Net" represents the "ETH", "volum" is a high-frequency word in "Capflow" and "bitcoin" is naturally the "BTC".

All in all, the model splits the "NFT" firstly because when people are talking about the NFT, they mostly do not care about the market Capflow but about the NFT activities. Then, the next key node is "play", where BTC and ETH have less relationship to this property.

Discussion and analysis¶

Decision tree 2 sets several parameters compared with the previous one. In this tree, GINI criteria are used rather than cross-entropy. Then, to avoid overfitting, "max_depth" is set to be 8.

Apparently, this decision tree based on the GINI is larger than the tree depending on the Cross entropy. However, the precision did not improve, where it perform worse when recognizing the Capflow and ETH.

Compared with the previous reasonable important features, important features in this decision tree starts to give more importance score on some unique words.

Discussion and analysis¶

By setting the "splitter='random'" and "max_features=30,", the decision tree model perform a high prediction. The fewer max features increased the randomness of the model tree. This time, by enlarging the max features, the tree becomes more stable than the previous two trees.

Some keywords or features in this tree provide further insights. For example, "join" rank the first importance of all features.

Compared with the previous two trees, this tree achieved a middle accuracy on the prediction. However, it should come to the attention that this model performs a weaker result when predicting the "Capflow".

Summary¶

Conclusion 1¶

The whole cryptocurrency market has been diversified into different sub-areas, at least including the "NFT", "Market Capflow", "BTC", "ETH". During this project, the result of the decision tree on tweets provides some key evidence. Some keywords or important features are play, volume, net, and bitcoin, where they are all the keywords belonging to each topic. For example, the "play" represents the culture of "NFT", the "Net" represents the "ETH", "volum" is a high-frequency word in "Capflow" and "bitcoin" is naturally the "BTC".

Conclusion 2¶

The boundary between different topics becomes clear although they arose from the same starting. In this project, the main reason why tree decision trees achieve a high precision is because of the distinctive different keywords between different topics. For example, when talking about the NFT, almost all the tweets are discussing a few keywords: airdrop, join, and play, where these keywords nearly are not discussed in other topics. Beyond that, due to the highly concentrated keywords, this gives a good opportunity for the decision tree to achieve such high precision. Therefore, some deeper work can be done on how to classify the tweets, especially in this area.
